<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n54144f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n54" href="#n54144f">N54 (VI.B.45)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n54all.htm#n54144f"> 144(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ame pot exterieres <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n54144f"> <li>FW unlocated</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">On reconna&icirc;t ici sans peine l&apos;&laquo;<mark>&acirc;me ext&eacute;rieure</mark>&raquo; d&eacute;crite par Sir James Frazer dans le <cite>Rameau d&apos;Or</cite>. Il en cite de nombreux exemples non moins caract&eacute;ristiques que celui de M. Meek. Dans ce dernier, le <mark>pot</mark> fabriqu&eacute; expr&egrave;s est &agrave; la fois le &laquo;double&raquo; de l&apos;homme qui l&apos;a command&eacute;, son &acirc;me ext&eacute;rieure (qu&apos;il y d&eacute;pose, ou plus exactement y incorpore), et son symbole, puisque le pot le repr&eacute;sente. A vrai dire, aucune de ces expressions, qui sont loin d&apos;&ecirc;tre &eacute;quivalentes, ne rend d&apos;une fa&ccedil;on satisfaisante ce qui occupe l&apos;esprit des Gabin. <br><font color="green">[We can easily recognize here the "external soul" described by Sir James Frazer in the <cite>Golden Palm</cite>. He cites many examples no less characteristic of that of Mr. Meek. In the latter, the pot made expressly is both the "double" of the man who ordered it, his outer soul (which he deposits there, or more exactly incorporates into it), and his symbol, since the pot represents him. In fact, none of these expressions, which are far from being equivalent, satisfactorily captures what occupies the minds of Gabins.]</font> <small> Lucian L&eacute;vy-Bruhl, <a name="LBEM" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#LBEM"><cite title="source">L'exp&eacute;rience mystique</cite></a> (1938) 219</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
